{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486680","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486680"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:41:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:41:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"158"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"158","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/158"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.1,0.05,0.74,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"158"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51775"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"158","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/158"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"158"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37075"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"2079"},{"type":"tags","id":"2757"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"67"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3722"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10734"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12265"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14079"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14479"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42006"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51775","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51775"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 80-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department after a motor vehicle crash in which she was the restrained driver. She states she felt dizzy with palpitations and chest tightness immediately prior to the accident. The paramedics reported that the patient was mildly confused when they arrived at the scene of the crash, with no traumatic injuries found during the primary and secondary survey. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is a non-smoker and does not drink alcohol. On examination, she appears well with a pulse rate of 55/min, blood pressure 110/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. Her physical examination is otherwise normal. Her ECG is shown below (Image). She received atropine in the emergency department prior to your review.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate long-term management strategy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Immediate cardioversion","Implantable cardiac defibrillator","Catheter ablation","Pacemaker insertion","PRN atropine"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s bradycardia and ECG is indicative of third-degree atrioventricular block, also known as complete heart block. The ECG shows P waves occurring at a regular rate, with QRS complexes also occurring at a regular rate. However, there is no relationship between the P waves and QRS complexes, indicating a complete dissociation between atrial and ventricular activity. Her dizziness and chest tightness likely preceded a syncopal episode while driving, leading to the crash.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs this patient has no relevant medical history and is not taking medications, the cause of her \u003Cstrong\u003Ecomplete heart block\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to have a reversible cause, such as medication toxicity. Due to this, \u003Cstrong\u003Einsertion of a permanent pacemaker\u003C/strong\u003E is required as it is the only treatment that will provide long-term resolution of symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate cardioversion\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as it is only indicated in those with atrial fibrillation or atrial flutter to restore normal sinus rhythm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtropine\u003C/strong\u003E is used for short term treatment of symptomatic bradycardia and is not a appropriate long term treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECatheter ablation\u003C/strong\u003E is currently used for treatment of tachycardia (e.g. supraventricular tachycardia and atrial flutter).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eimplantable cardiac defibrillator\u003C/strong\u003E detects life-threatening ventricular tachycardia\u0027s  and automatically delivers an electric shock to prevent sudden cardiac death. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Complete heart block will require pacemaker insertion.","It is important to look for reversible causes prior to proceeding with permanent pacemaker insertion."],"references":["Levis JT. ECG Diagnosis: Complete Heart Block. Perm J. 2011;15(2):90. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3140757/","American Heart Association. Part 7.3: Management of Symptomatic Bradycardia and Tachycardia. Circulation. 2005;112(24):IV-67-IV-77. Available at: https://www.ahajournals.org/doi/10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.105.166558","Kistler PM. Catheter ablation techniques in managing arrhythmias. Aust Fam Physician. 2007;36(7):512-517. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/61d95c6a-98db-4fea-9119-e2df949efaa3/200707kistler1.pdf","DiMarco JP. Implantable cardioverter-defibrillators. N. Engl. J. Med. 2003;349(19):1836\u20131847. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/14602883/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37075"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"158"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20683"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20683","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20683"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/o6dHOkmVmw0wpRbfMtFISbSaMiL6sz.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/o6dHOkmVmw0wpRbfMtFISbSaMiL6sz.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":621}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37075","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37075"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-28T21:29:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-28T21:30:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"158"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51775"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/